      {
        "paragraph_index": 3,
        "text": "### Chemical Insight\n\n**Ethylenediamine binds Ni²⁺ roughly 10⁴·⁶ ≈ 40,000 times more strongly** than ammonia in the first complexation step. This dramatic enhancement is a textbook illustration of the **chelate effect**: ethylenediamine is a bidentate ligand that forms a five-membered chelate ring with Ni²⁺, coordinating through both nitrogen atoms simultaneously. The entropic advantage of displacing two monodentate water molecules with a single chelating ligand, combined with the favorable ring geometry, accounts for the ~4.6 log-unit gain in stability. This is why ethylenediamine complexes are widely used in analytical chemistry and metal-ion separations where high complex stability is required.\n\n*Data source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (SRD-46).*",
